rn obsessions with tidiness and cleanliness to our desire to attain perfect bodies, notions of disabilities as examples of human insufficiency proliferate. These disability practices infuse more general modes of social obedience at work today. Consequently, this important study explains how disabled people are instrumental to charting the passage from a disciplinary society to one based upon regulation of the self.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh  adisability, eugenics, defective, social norms, biology, deviance, extermination, institutionalization, marriage laws, charity systems, regulation, surveillance, enclosure, segregation, perfection, public participation, inclusion, reintegration, visibility, science, film, popular culture, medical model, nonfiction, sociology.1 aMitchell, David T., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z97831106353860 cprintz978022676731440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226767307423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226767307/original  a978-3-11-063538-6  University of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles